"German Secret Ink" Recipe
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/german-secret-ink1.jpg
                    
					Two of the documents feature recipes written in French for “German secret ink” as well as methods for making it reappear.
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Vanishing Ink Formula
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/secret-writing.jpg
                    
					A memo provides a recipe for vanishing ink (a “solution of nitrate and soda in water”) and advises soaking a handkerchief or starched collar in the mixture. The material can then be dried and rehydrated to release the solution at a later time. Several concoctions can be used to develop the secret writing, according to the document.
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Instructions for Steaming Open Letters
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/sealed-envelope.jpg
                    
					A handwritten message provides instructions for secretly opening envelopes by steaming letters over a chemical bath. “Do not inhale fumes,” it warns the reader.
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Vanishing Ink Formulas from Chemist
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/writing-instruments.jpg
                    
					A letter from an assistant chemist offers seven vanishing ink formulas along with the suggestion that they be used with a quill pen. Some of the recipes, the chemist explains, “will doubtless exert a very corrosive action on steel pens.”
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Invisible Photography and Ink Instructions
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/book-page1.jpg
                    
					Four pages of research and instructions on invisible photography and ink outline various methods for writing and exposing clandestine messages.
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Invisible Photography and Ink Instructions
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/book-page2.jpg
                    
					The confidential information contained in these pages was compiled by Theodore Kytka, a San Francisco handwriting expert, according to the document.
